'''Sean Furey''' (born August 31, 1982) is an [[United States|American]] [[javelin throw]]er.  He has placed in the top three at the U.S. National Championships three times, winning the javelin event in 2010.  In 2009, he represented the United States at the World Championships, finishing 12th.  In 2012, Furey placed fourth at the [[2012 United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|Olympic Trials]].  Since the first and second placers had not met the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Qualification#Qualifying Standards|Olympic "A" Standard]] and Furey had, he qualified to represent the [[United States at the 2012 Summer Olympics]].

==Early life==
Sean Furey was born August 31, 1982 to Kathy Furey (who later became Kathy Stupak by marriage).<ref name=profile /><ref name=punches />  He grew up in [[Methuen, Massachusetts]] with his younger brother Ryan and began throwing the [[Javelin throw|javelin]] while at [[Methuen High School]].<ref name=set /> He won two state javelin championships and in 2000, won the National Scholastic Championship.<ref name=profile />  During his senior season, Furey led his school to the [[Merrimack Valley Conference]] title and was named to the All-Scholastic team by the ''[[Boston Herald]]''.<ref name=earns>{{cite news|title=Former Herald All-Scholastic Sean Furey of Methuen earns a spot on the Olympic team|date=June 26, 2012|work=High School Insider Blog|publisher=''Boston Herald''|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/blogs/sports/high_school/index.php/2012/06/26/former-herald-all-scholastic-sean-furey-of-methuen-earns-a-spot-on-the-olympic-team/|accessdate=July 24, 2012}}</ref>  He graduated from Methuen in 2000.<ref name=profile />  Furey also played on the school's [[American football|football]] team.<ref name=earns />

After high school, Furey attended [[Dartmouth]].  He graduated in 2005 with a 3.80 GPA and an engineering degree.<ref name=profile>{{cite web|title=Athlete Bios: Sean Furey|publisher=USA Track & Field|url=http://www.usatf.org/Athlete-Bios/Sean-Furey.aspx|accessdtae=July 24, 2012}}</ref>

==Athletic career==
At Dartmouth, Furey set the school record in javelin, with a distance of {{convert|242|ft|3|in|adj=on}}.<ref name=profile />  In 2005, he won the [[Ivy League]] championship and was named the "Scholar Athlete of the Year" by the [[U.S. Track & Field and Cross Country Coaches Association]].<ref name=profile />  At the 2005 [[NCAA Men's Outdoor Track and Field Championship|NCAA Outdoor Championships]], he placed third with a throw of {{convert|73.83|m}}.<ref name=profile />

After college, Furey moved to [[San Diego]] to train.<ref name=set />  At the [[2008 United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|2008 Olympic Trials]], he placed seventh. In 2009, he placed third in the [[USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships|National Championships]] and qualified for Worlds with a throw of {{convert|76.16|m}}.<ref name=profile />  At the [[2009 World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]], he was in fifth place among the "B" group after the qualification round of the javelin throw.  However, he did not match that success in the final and finished in 12th place out of 12 competitors that made the final.<ref name=profile /> 

Furey won the 2010 National Championships with a throw of {{convert|79.86|m}}.<ref name=profile />  In 2011, he finished in second place, recording a distance of {{convert|77.99|m}}.<ref name=profile />  At the [[2011 Pan American Games]], Furey placed fourth.<ref name=profile />

At the [[2012 United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|2012 Olympic Trials]], Furey was battling a back injury.<ref name=set />
He placed fourth, throwing the javelin {{convert|77.86|m}}.<ref name=profile />  Two weeks prior to the Trials, he had met the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Qualification#Qualifying Standards|Olympic "A" Standard]] of {{convert|82.00|m}} by throwing a new personal best {{convert|82.73|m}} in [[Lisle, Illinois]].  First and second place did not make the make standard, allowing Furey and fifth place finisher [[Cyrus Hostetler]] to make the Olympic team.<ref name=set>{{cite news|title=Methuen native Sean Furey set for London|author=John Connolly|date=July 20, 2012|work=Boston Herald|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/olympics/other/view/20220720sound_plan_and_furey_methuen_native__set_for_london/srvc=home&position=also|accessdate=July 24, 2012}}</ref>  After the meet, he remarked "It's mixed emotions, fourth place vs. the Olympic team&nbsp;... It's bittersweet. I just didn't execute like I needed."<ref name=punches />  In London, Furey will compete in the preliminary round of the javelin throw on August 8.  If he advances to the final, he will compete again on August 11.  He enters the competition with the longest throw by an American this year.<ref name=punches>{{cite news|title=Methuen's Furey punches ticket to London Olympics|date=June 26, 2012|work=The Eagle-Tribune|author=Michael Muldoon|url=http://www.eagletribune.com/sports/x439053438/Methuens-Furey-punches-ticket-to-London-Olympics|accessdate=July 24, 2012}}</ref>  He is ranked number 16 in the world.<ref name=punches />

Furey is coached by former Olympian [[Todd Reich]] and sponsored by [[Mizuno Corp.|Mizuno]].<ref name=set />  "Todd is a talented guy," says Furey. "He knows what the elite javelin throwers are doing."<ref name=set />  Furey says he has no plans to retire anytime soon.  "I won't quit until my arm falls off," he said.<ref name=punches />

==Personal life==
Furey currently lives in San Diego, California with his wife Matthan "Mattie" Chatterton-Richmond.<ref name=punches /><ref name=set />  He works part time at [[Raytheon]] as a [[mechanical engineer]] doing what he describes as "bomb-proofing electronics" for the [[United States Navy]].<ref name=set />   When asked why he chose to continue pursuing the javelin, instead of concentrating on his higher paying engineering career, Furey remarked "Missing out on money, I don't care. We have everything we need and more. Making money won't make me happier. Being on the Olympic team will make me happier."<ref name=punches />

